              <table id="EditorialReviewsPanel" class="ReviewSection" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%"><tr><td>
	
                <DIV class="ReviewHeading">John's Review:</DIV>
                <span id="Label1">I recently wrote and delivered <a href="http://www.objectsharp.com">ObjectSharp's</a> Services class. One of the key ideas in the class was that systems are implemented using modules that are connected via messages. 
<br><br>I became aware of Gregor and Bobby's book based on a recommendation from Sean McGrath. However, I deliberately avoided reading it while writing my class since I wanted to craft my own story.
<br><br>Once I had a chance to sit down and read this book, I was amazed by how effective it is in teaching a pattern language for describing asynchronous message-based systems. Gregor and Bobby obviously spent a lot of time categorizing the patterns in the book and carefully crafting them into a comprehensive cross-referenced "story".
<br><br>They also did a great job of inventing a series of icons that are used repeatedly throughout the discussions of various patterns. They are great at reinforcing the names of the patterns, and your eye quickly gets trained to recognize composite patterns that emerge during the detailed discussions of the individual patterns.
<br><br>You don't need to wait for the web service vendors to come up with an implementation for WS-ReliableMessaging. You can apply the patterns in this book using many of today's existing technologies. The book strives to be technology-neutral, and presents implementations of various patterns using many vendor's technologies. While this is somewhat jolting to the reader, it also serves to whet your appetite for what implementations look like on competing platforms.
<br><br>If you are interested in service orientation, and the impact that async message-based systems will have on your organization's applications, you owe it to yourself to purchase a copy of this book for every member of your team. Much like the seminal Refactoring book by Martin Fowler, the pattern language that it introduces into your team is absolutely invaluable.
<br><br>At ObjectSharp, we are making this book mandatory reading for all of our consultants who are involved in systems integration. </span>
              
</td></tr></table>
